ce:section.ce:para:
Although CPDs is efficient sensor for the recognition of Cu2+ and S2−, the quenching mechanism of the fluorescence emission needs to be clarified by using fluorescence lifetimes, Zeta potentials, UV–Vis and FT-IR spectroscopy and XPS for extension to practical applications. Initially, the fluorescence lifetime of CPDs decreased from 11.34 to 7.27 ns with the gradual increase of Cu2+ concentration implying that this is a dynamic quenching process (Fig. 5
                     a, Fig. S9) [53]. As shown in the Fig. S10, quenching constants (Ksv) = 1.143 × 104 M−1, such a high value clearly indicates that the interaction between CPDs and Cu2+ is clearly strong. Interestingly, the change in fluorescence lifetime is dominated by the fast component of the surface functional groups. The Zeta potential of the aqueous solution of CPDs increased from −12.335 to 2.674 mV after the introduction of Cu2+, reflecting the potential neutralization that normally occurs when Cu2+ have a higher binding attraction to –COOH and –OH, which are negatively charged (Fig. 5b). The accompanying UV spectroscopic analysis carried out can also proves the reaction of Cu2+ with CPDs, as a new broad peak in the wavelength range of 750–850 nm is generated which is defined as Cu-O band, while the previous peak at 350 nm of CPDs is substantially weakened, pointing directly to the disruption of the conjugated structure of the internal chromophore due to the involvement of Cu2+ (Fig. 5c) [55]. It is notable that the stretching vibrations of O-H/N-H at 3347 cm−1 are considerably reduced in the FT-IR spectroscopy (Fig. 5d) [28], and the previous stretching vibrations of C-H largely disappear, as well as the peaks of C=O and C=C at 1703 cm−1 and 1622 cm−1, which are also dramatically reduced. However, the C-O peak at 1161 cm−1 is significantly enhanced and a new peak at 661 cm−1 appears representing Cu-O, the above supports the coordination of Cu2+ to nitrogen- and oxygen-containing functional groups and the disruption of the conjugated aromatic ring. The analysis of the XPS spectra confirms the above conclusion, revealing that the N1s are also significantly weaker in the full spectrum and can be fitted to the new bond Cu-N in the split peaks [56], while the intensity of the CO in the fine spectrum O1s is reduced by nearly 60%. The presence of Cu2p in the spectrum of CPDs+Cu2+ is allocated to Cu2p3/2 (935.52 eV) and Cu2p1/2 (951.00 eV) (Fig. 5e-h). The strong binding constant (Ka) of 1.40 × 105 M−1 calculated earlier for CPDs with Cu2+ also supports our speculation (Fig. S11). Summarizing, the mechanism of fluorescence quenching of CPDs: the paramagnetic action of the Cu2+ and their coordination with the functional groups (–COOH, –OH and –NH2) on the surface of CPDs leads to charge transfer. (Fig. 6
                     ).
